<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/books-arts <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/books-arts" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 14 日星期一 18:07:44 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[A Table Outside? More Diners Say No Way]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>餐馆称热浪和烟雾损害了他们的户外用餐业务<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001126271"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833543?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在热浪期间，顾客纷纷避开露台，从而影响了餐厅夏季的销售。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Richard B. Levine/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001126271"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/heather-haddon" itemprop="url" rel="author">希瑟·哈登</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wendy-guzman" itemprop="url" rel="author">温迪·古兹曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 9:00（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-table-outside-more-diners-say-no-way-41d098aa"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国各地的严重高温给餐馆带来了损失。</p><p>业主们表示，在热浪期间，顾客会避开露台，这成为许多餐厅夏季销售的一个主要来源。行业数据显示，7 月和 8 月的访问量较今年早些时候有所下降，Chuy&#39;s 和 Cheesecake Factory 等连锁店报告今年夏天的户外业务有所下降。</p><p> “没有人会坐在华氏 100 度的露台上，”德克萨斯州 Chuy&#39;s 首席执行官史蒂夫·希斯洛普 (Steve Hislop) 在 8 月 3 日的财报电话会议上表示。</p><p>运营商和行业团体表示，由于餐馆长时间开足空调，公用事业费用也在上升。</p><p>今年夏天气温攀升至<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/june-hottest-on-record-heat-b222c05c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">有记录以来的最高水平，</a>损害了酒店、体育、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-farmers-livestock-crops-ce555ffd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">农业</a>和许多其他行业。在德克萨斯州等州，连续几周气温超过 100 度预计<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-dont-want-to-be-here-anymore-the-economic-cost-of-houstons-heat-3cf69016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">会降低整体经济生产力</a>。</p><p>餐馆正在与高温和烟雾作斗争，因为许多经营者正在努力争取现金短缺的消费者的销售，并应对食品、劳动力和其他成本的高通胀。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833553?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cheesecake Factory 报告称，今年夏天户外业务有所下降。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的玛吉·香农</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>OpenTable 的数据显示，与去年同期相比，8 月上旬亚利桑那州、佛罗里达州和佐治亚州餐厅的就餐人数总体下降了 6% 至 8%。这家预订科技公司还记录了今年夏天其他热门州的用餐人数下降的情况，包括德克萨斯州和北卡罗来纳州。</p><p> “今年夏天确实感觉不一样，”德克萨斯餐馆协会贸易集团首席公共事务官凯尔西·埃里克森·斯特鲁弗特说。 “让人们出来有点困难。”</p><p>根据小型企业劳动力应用程序 Homebase 的数据，7 月份餐厅和酒吧的员工数量较上月下降了 1.5%，其中圣安东尼奥、新奥尔良和凤凰城等本月录得高温的城市的员工数量大幅下降。 Homebase 表示，销量下降可能是由于极端气温扰乱了消费者支出和人流量。</p><p>工人权益倡导者在改善餐厅工人工作条件的运动中越来越多地<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-is-it-too-hot-to-keep-working-in-most-states-companies-decide-9797ae18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将热量作为一个问题</a>。一些人正在推动更好地执行现有标准和额外的联邦室内供暖法规，以便在气温升高时为员工提供休息和水。</p><p>北卡罗来纳州阿什维尔一家餐厅的厨师阿丽亚娜·林格菲尔德 (Ariana Lingerfeldt) 在 8 月 9 日的一次活动中说道：“我们在厨房最凉爽的一侧看到了 86 度的温度。”她也是餐厅机会中心联合工人倡导组织的成员。以获得更多热量标准。 “空调跟不上设备。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="465" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833607?width=700&amp;height=465" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">许多餐厅在 Covid-19 大流行初期就设立了露台，现在依靠它们来推动夏季销售。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：蒂莫西·福克斯摄影</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些餐馆经营者表示，他们正在为员工提供更多的饮水和休息时间，因为尽管有空调，厨房温度仍会急剧上升。</p><p>许多餐厅在 Covid-19 大流行初期<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/restaurants-spend-big-for-upgraded-outdoor-dining-with-quicker-service-elaborate-decor-for-winter-11633599000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">就设立了露台</a>，并开始依靠它们来推动夏季销售。例如，纽约市准备从 4 月到 11 月永久<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/outdoor-dining-saved-restaurants-but-making-it-permanent-is-complicated-11648925954?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">扩大道路户外就餐范围</a>，支持者表示露台有助于餐馆维持销售和就业。</p><p>现在，一些餐馆老板表示，当气温飙升或野火烟雾弥漫时，露台销售就会枯竭。</p><p>芝加哥市中心 City Social 餐厅的总经理马克·霍赫穆斯 (Marc Hochmuth) 说：“当阳光照在上面时，那里简直就是滚烫的。”该餐厅设有露台。 Hochmuth 表示，今年夏天气温飙升时，他的生意整体下降了约 20%。</p><p> 20 岁的宾夕法尼亚州居民佐伊·迪恩-尼尔 (Zoe Dean-Neil) 8 月份在芝加哥度假，她说，在炎热的天气里走了一天后，她选择在空调里吃饭。 “我不想坐在外面出汗，”她说。</p><p>今年初夏，加拿大山火<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-east-coast-gets-a-taste-of-what-its-like-living-with-wildfires-f4330a14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">飘入美国的烟雾</a>也影响了该国部分地区餐馆的生意。来自芝加哥的 31 岁管理顾问约翰·杜布克 (John DuBuque) 表示，在这座城市烟雾弥漫的时期，他曾试图在外面喝一杯葡萄酒，但后来后悔了。</p><p> “这不是氛围，”杜比克说，他说他现在根据空气质量指数做出更多户外用餐决定。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=73DA72E0-DF39-4F23-973C-AEEBEF455473&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-table-outside-more-diners-say-no-way-41d098aa&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国西南部的一个巨大的热穹正在推动菲尼克斯和拉斯维加斯的气温创下三位数的新高。新的 Maxar 卫星照片显示了这些城市的发展如何导致了酷热。插图：卢卡·德帕东<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>餐馆老板正在努力应对天气变化。亚利桑那州坦佩市百英里酿酒公司老板苏·里格勒 (Sue Rigler) 表示，她正在室外啤酒冷却装置上喷水并安装额外的风扇，以保持凉爽。她还削减了劳动力，以应对销售放缓（她将其归因于炎热天气）。</p><p> “七月是非常艰难的一个月，”里格勒说。 “我们终于在 108 分取得了突破，他们称之为突破。”</p><p>新墨西哥州 La Posta de Mesilla 和 Hacienda de Mesilla 的老板汤姆·哈钦森 (Tom Hutchinson) 表示，他的酒店和餐馆正在推销冰镇啤酒和玛格丽塔酒以吸引顾客。他还希望在夜间气温可能降至华氏 90 度时，让人们继续来到土坯房周围的户外空间。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>今年夏天你在室内还是室外用餐的次数更多了？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “我们州没有湿度，你可以忍受，”他说。</p><p>从长远来看，餐厅经营者正在努力适应更多气候驱动的变量。</p><p>费城 FCM Hospitality 集团旗下餐厅、酒吧和户外快闪场所的所有者阿夫拉姆·霍尼克 (Avram Hornik) 表示，由于连续几周的高温和降雨，今年夏天他的销售额下降了 30%。他说，六月份的烟雾天气并没有起到什么作用。</p><p> “我把它看作是一个农民。天气控制一切，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Heather Haddon ( <a href="mailto:heather.haddon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">heather.haddon@wsj.com)</a>和 Wendy Guzman ( <a href="mailto:wendy.guzman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wendy.guzman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-table-outside-more-diners-say-no-way-41d098aa</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-table-outside-more-diners-say-no-way-41d098aa<author><![CDATA[Heather HaddonWendy Guzman]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>住宿/餐厅/酒吧</category><category>餐厅/餐饮供应商</category><category>全方位服务餐厅</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>住宿</category><category>餐馆</category><category>酒吧</category><category>餐饮业</category><category>全方位服务餐厅</category><category>闲暇</category><category>艺术</category><category>款待</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ozempic Settles the Obesity Debate: It’s Biology Over Willpower]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>减肥药物影响大脑的方式有助于研究人员了解身体如何调节体重<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834611/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>埃米尔·伦多夫/华尔街日报<span>埃米尔·伦多夫/华尔街日报</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129880"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129880"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/betsy-mckay" itemprop="url" rel="author">贝特西·麦凯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Ozempic 和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-drugs-that-are-gaining-on-ozempic-71cdeb51?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">类似药物</a>正在改变世界<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-weight-loss-body-positivity-marketing-6e918f8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对肥胖的认识</a>。这与意志力无关<strong>：</strong>而是与生物学有关。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-diabetes-drug-weight-loss-c0e03c25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">强大的新型</a>糖尿病和减肥药物的成功表明化学对于确定一个人的体重有多么重要。大脑是人体的首席化学家，负责调节食欲，使许多人难以减肥并保持体重。根据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mounjaro-eli-lilly-weight-loss-new-study-5f7661cc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新药支持的</a>多年研究，大脑决定了它希望人们携带多少脂肪。</p><p>这个量就像表盘上的设置，或者许多研究人员所说的“设定点”或“防御脂肪量”。大脑通过调节一个人的饮食量来维持刻度设置或设定点。一些肥胖研究人员表示，Ozempic、它的姊妹药物 Wegovy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-mounjaro-weight-loss-drug-wegovy-eli-lilly-66f2906?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">和另一种药物 Mounjaro</a>可以降低刻度盘设置或设定点，通过作用于大脑来减少饥饿感并让人更快感到饱足<strong>。</strong></p><p>他们说，只要患者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-stop-weight-loss-ea925ae1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">服用药物</a>，新的设定点就会持续存在。在开始服用其中一种药物之前吃得很多的患者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-weight-loss-drugs-strains-relationships-327ab217?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">会感觉不那么饥饿</a>，并且很快就会有饱腹感——有时在吃完一片披萨后，他们曾经吃掉了整个披萨。</p><p> “这与意志力或个人选择无关，”虚拟医疗减肥诊所 Form 的内分泌学家兼首席医疗官弗洛伦西亚·哈尔珀林 (Florencia Halperin) 博士说。 “这与你的大脑驱动行为有关。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=35CD7B9E-3215-4417-9DEE-8FF9D9BBEDC9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fweight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">糖尿病药物可能成为治疗行为问题和成瘾的有效方法。 《华尔街日报》的丹妮拉·埃尔南德斯 (Daniela Hernandez) 详细剖析了它们的工作原理以及它们如何永远改变精神病学。图片插图：伊丽莎白·斯梅洛夫<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pediatricians-recommend-weight-loss-drugs-for-obese-children-11673213563?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与肥胖的斗争</a>中，这些药物及其对生物学的见解已经到了一个岌岌可危的地步。尽管美国人每年花费数十亿美元来减肥， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/more-states-show-prevalence-of-obesity-cdc-finds-11631734589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">但超重的人数却在</a>不断增加。根据该机构的数据，近 42% 的美国成年人患有肥胖症<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a>最新的<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">政府统计数据</a>，比 1999 年的 31% 有所上升<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/childhood.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">。五分之一</a>也是如此<strong>&nbsp;</strong>孩子们。</p><p>肥胖者更容易<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-decades-of-progress-america-backslides-on-heart-disease-11561129106?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">患心脏病</a>、中风和糖尿病。治疗它们<a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0247307#pone.0247307.ref002" target="_blank" class="icon none">每年花费</a>超过 1700 亿美元。 Wegovy 已被证明可以<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wegovy-weight-loss-drug-heart-attack-stroke-570f435e?mod=hp_lead_pos6&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">降低心血管风险</a>，而 Mounjaro 正在研究其是否具有额外的健康益处。</p><p>新药打破了一些长期以来关于体重和健康的假设。 “这些药物已经证明，患者是对的：这不是他们的错，”肥胖治疗专家、威尔康奈尔医学院代谢研究教授路易斯·阿龙博士说。</p><p>他和许多其他研究肥胖或开新药的专家为生产这些药物的公司提供建议或进行研究。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834335?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ozempic 注射笔是一种新型药物，颠覆了人们长期以来对体重的假设。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jaap Arriens/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乔恩·韦斯曼</p>2020 年，当他寻求减肥帮助时，体重约为 300 磅，处于糖尿病前期，有患心脏病的风险。这位 46 岁的人在波士顿从事抵押贷款银行和房地产工作，曾尝试限制食物，但总是感到更饿。 “我每天无法摄入 2,000 卡路里热量，”他说。 “我大概收到了 4,000 美元。”<p></p><p>他重新开始使用他之前尝试过的上一代减肥药 Saxenda。他减掉了大约 30 磅，但随后就达到了稳定状态。</p><p> 2021 年 9 月，他与 Halperin 医生商议，后者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-you-cant-find-wegovy-the-weight-loss-drug-11670108199?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开了 Wegovy。</a>他的饥饿感很快就减轻了。他不再渴望洋葱圈、通心粉和奶酪以及其他他曾经在与朋友的马拉松晚餐中吃过的重口味食物，现在更喜欢绿色和蛋白质。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835101?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乔恩·韦斯曼 (Jon Weisman) 正在服用 Wegovy。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·韦斯曼</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>几个月前，他的体重达到了 180 磅的目标，目前仍在继续服用该药，有时他还得打电话去几家药店寻找药物。 “这是我余生都必须接受的治疗，”他说。他停止了服用的两种降压药物，改用低剂量的降胆固醇药物，并且不再处于糖尿病前期。他现在吃得更多了，是为了维持体重而不是减肥。</p><p>肥胖症的流行是新旧力量相互碰撞的产物，这些力量在像韦斯曼这样的人身上发生了碰撞：人类生物学在数千年的寻找生计的斗争中形成；大部分时间都是坐着的生活；以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cake-could-be-the-secret-to-teaching-kids-about-healthy-eating-habits-c4947362?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大量廉价的加工食品</a>。</p><p>研究表明，薯片、苏打水和其他廉价加工食品是罪魁祸首，因为它们的热量、糖、盐和脂肪含量很高，而且<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-end-of-craving-review-why-you-cant-eat-just-one-11635977800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">让人难以放下</a>。与吃蔬菜、全谷物<a href="https://www.cell.com/cell-metabolism/fulltext/S1550-4131(19)30248-7" target="_blank" class="icon none">、</a>根据 2019 年的一项研究，鱼和其他未加工食品。</p><p>对于某些人来说，高热量食物尤其成问题。</p><p>至少有 1,500 个基因与体重有关。哥本哈根大学<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVO" class="company-name">诺和诺德</a>基金会代谢研究中心和伊坎学院专注于肥胖遗传学的教授露丝·洛斯 (Ruth Loos) 表示，有些人在遗传上容易发胖，具体取决于这些基因中变异的组合。西奈山医学博士。这些基因通常在大脑中发挥作用。</p><p>大脑中控制呼吸、心跳和其他基本功能的原始部分与激素和中枢神经系统协作，确定身体想要拥有多少脂肪并将其保持在设定点。这个系统是由人类数千年来为生存而觅食而形成的。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Ozempic 和其他减肥药如何改变您对肥胖的理解？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>当一个人需要能量来达到或维持设定值时，大脑会发出饥饿信号，当达到或超过设定值时，大脑会发出饱腹感信号。这就是为什么那些为了抗病而减肥的人一旦康复就会感到饥饿，或者为什么人们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-ozempic-treat-binge-eating-for-some-the-answer-is-yes-dbdc009f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在吃得过多时会感到不舒服</a>。研究表明，这也是为什么人们 <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4989512/" target="_blank" class="icon none">——比如《减肥达人》电视剧中的一些参与者</a>——即使在尝试减肥后体重也会反弹。</p><p>设定点不是固定的：它会在人的一生中自然变化。婴儿会失去体内脂肪。女性在怀孕<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-if-we-could-get-rid-of-menopause-7adbc4e0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">和更年期</a>期间体重会增加。它可以带来微小的改变，使一个人增加或减少几磅。</p><p>然而，波士顿肥胖与代谢研究所所长李·卡普兰博士表示<strong>，</strong>肥胖者的设定点系统已经失常。体脂刻度盘移至新的更高设定点。</p><p>卡普兰说，肥胖会导致暴饮暴食，而不是相反。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834339?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">科学家们越来越多地认为，肥胖流行是由于大量高热量加工食品、久坐的生活方式和人类生物学的共同作用造成的。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Chona Kasinger/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>新药基于激素<strong>&nbsp;</strong>称为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-diabetes-drug-weight-loss-c0e03c25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">胰高血糖素样肽 1</a>或 GLP-1，主要在肠道内壁和大脑中响应食物而分泌。药物猎人最初对 GLP-1 感兴趣，因为它在调节血糖方面发挥着重要作用。第一个 GLP-1 药物于 2005 年被批准用于治疗糖尿病。</p><p> Wegovy 是美国食品和药物管理局批准<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/employers-cut-off-access-to-weight-loss-drugs-for-workers-cb277a44?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于抗肥胖治疗的</a>唯一 GLP-1 药物，而 Ozempic 则具有较低剂量的相同活性成分索马鲁肽， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-runs-low-for-diabetes-patients-as-weight-loss-use-surges-286bf21a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">被批准用于治疗糖尿病</a>。预计 FDA 很快就会批准 Mounjaro 用于减肥。 Mounjaro 已被批准用于治疗 2 型糖尿病，除了 GLP-1 之外，它还模仿一种名为 GIP 的激素的作用。</p><p>密歇根大学外科教授兼密歇根营养肥胖研究中心主任 Randy Seeley 表示，这些药物本质上是通过激活下丘脑和脑干中调节体重和食欲的 GLP-1 受体来降低设定点。这些药物还间接到达大脑中涉及奖赏感觉和冲动控制的神经元。</p><p> “我们正在不断寻找对这些药物有反应的最关键的神经元，”他说。</p><p>西利说，一旦患者达到新的设定点，他们的一些食欲就会恢复——他们不再感觉吃得过多——但药物会将他们保持在新的水平。他说，如果患者停止服药，新的设定值就不再有效，这就是人们体重反弹的原因。</p><p>一些研究人员表示，设定点概念很难得到明确证明。这些药物的制造商诺和诺德和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LLY" class="">礼来</a>公司表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>他们的药物在服用时可以减少饥饿感并增加饱腹感。</p><p>卡普兰说，研究人员想要弄清楚是什么导致某些人的设定值大幅上升，从而导致肥胖：“目前，这是一个黑匣子。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/11004b12-051f-4044-aa8a-823e293913dd.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给 Betsy McKay： <a href="mailto:betsy.mckay@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">betsy.mckay@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173<author><![CDATA[Betsy McKay]]></author><category>华尔街日报健康</category><category>药品</category><category>科学研究服务</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>特殊药物/药物</category><category>激素产品</category><category>糖尿病药物</category><category>医学研究服务</category><category>药物发现/开发</category><category>医疗保健支持服务</category><category>诊断/医学研究服务</category><category>生物学</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>化学</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>肥胖</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>生物学</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>化学</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>肥胖</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>社会问题</category><category>药品</category><category>科学研究服务</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>专门药物</category><category>药物</category><category>激素产品</category><category>糖尿病药物</category><category>医学研究服务</category><category>药物发现</category><category>发展</category><category>医疗保健支持服务</category><category>诊断</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Economic Losers in the New World Order]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>巨额补贴和不断抬头的保护主义正在颠覆数十年的自由贸易。从英国到新加坡，较小的国家正在落后。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834926/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="印度尼西亚莫罗瓦利工业园附近交通中的工人，该工业园是镍相关产业的中心。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>印度尼西亚莫罗瓦利工业园附近交通中的工人，该工业园是镍相关产业的中心。 Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images <span>Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ed-ballard" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾德·巴拉德</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰森·道格拉斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-emont" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔恩·埃蒙特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>世界上最大的经济体在一场残酷的竞争中提供巨额补贴，以赢得未来的产业。失败者：所有付不起钱的国家。</p><p>针对制造电池、太阳能设备和其他绿色技术的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-legislation-inflation-reduction-act-small-towns-eb0ce798?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新税收抵免</a>正在吸引<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-biggest-winners-in-americas-climate-law-foreign-companies-c672e09d" target="_blank" class="icon none">大量资金</a>涌入美国，欧盟正试图以自己的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-to-unveil-clean-tech-plans-in-bid-to-rival-u-s-china-a391ef5a" target="_blank" class="icon none">绿色能源</a>支持计划来应对。日本宣布计划借债 1500 亿美元，为绿色技术投资浪潮提供资金。所有这些国家都在努力<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-eu-advance-buyers-club-for-ev-battery-minerals-5288287e" target="_blank" class="icon none">减少对中国的依赖</a>，中国在电池和制造电池的矿物等领域处于领先地位。</p><p>现在，一些规模较小的企业正在被抛在后面。许多经济体都是灵活的经济体，在几十年的自由贸易中不断崛起，但在激进的产业政策新时代却处于不利地位。英国和新加坡等工业化国家在提供补贴方面缺乏与最大经济集团竞争的规模。印度尼西亚等新兴市场原本希望利用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">其自然资源</a>来攀登经济阶梯，但也受到了这种转变的威胁。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834966?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>德国政府向英特尔提供了 110 亿美元的补贴，用于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-tsmc-to-build-first-european-chip-plant-in-germany-155e4d8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">建设两座半导体工厂</a>，总理奥拉夫·肖尔茨 (Olaf Scholz) 称这是德国历史上最大的外国直接投资。政府承诺的融资远高于新加坡贸工部的年度预算。</p><p> “让我坦白地告诉你们：我们承担不起比大公司出价更高的代价，”副总理黄循财在最近的一次政治集会上对支持者说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834210?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英特尔首席执行官帕特·基辛格(Pat Gelsinger)和德国总理奥拉夫·舒尔茨(Olaf Scholz)于6月签署了一项协议，让英特尔在德国建造两家半导体工厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Chris Emil JanssEn/ddp/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>对于许多在英国培育的科技公司来说，增长在于其他地方。英国电池技术初创公司 Nexeon 在政府资助的帮助下在牛津附近开发了自己的技术，去年筹集了超过 2 亿美元。它的第一家商业工厂将设在韩国，随后可能会在北美设立一家工厂。</p><p> “但遗憾的是，英国不是这样，”纳科星公司首席执行官斯科特·布朗(Scott Brown)表示。如果政府不加大对电池行业的支持，纳科星公司并不认为这种情况会发生改变。</p><p>英国为数不多的本土电池制造商之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UK/XLON/AMTE" class="">AMTE Power</a>表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>鉴于美国和欧洲提供的补贴存在差异，该公司可能会重新考虑在苏格兰设立一家耗资 2 亿多美元的工厂的计划。电动汽车初创公司 Arrival 去年表示，以税收优惠为由，希望将生产重点放在美国而不是英国。</p><p>作为《通货膨胀削减法案》的一部分，美国为清洁能源提供了 3690 亿美元的激励措施和资金， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-green-subsidies-are-attracting-billions-of-dollars-to-red-states-11674488426?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">外国投资也带来了意外之财</a>。德国汽车制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/BMW" class="company-name">宝马</a>刚刚在南卡罗来纳州破土动工建设一座新电池工厂。韩国公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hyundai-motor-lg-energy-to-build-4-3-bln-battery-jv-in-u-s-97991f73?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">现代和</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KR/XKRX/066570" class="company-name">LG</a>宣布斥资 43 亿美元在佐治亚州建设电池厂。日本松下公司正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/panasonic-energy-kansas-to-partner-on-4-billion-ev-battery-factory-11657754596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">堪萨斯州建设一家工厂</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834214?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">工人们正在为堪萨斯州德索托附近的松下电动汽车电池工厂进行场地准备。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：查理·里德尔/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>解除全球化</h3><p>补贴竞赛标志着几十年来打破国家间贸易和投资壁垒的经济一体化又迈出了一步。</p><p>全球化将韩国和台湾等曾经贫穷的国家转变为高科技发达经济体，使数亿人摆脱了贫困。西方消费者获得了大量负担得起的消费品和更高的生活水平。技术进步和新的管理理念以及商品和金融资源也更加自由地在国家之间流动。</p><p>该模型的成本也很高。随着制造业工作转移到亚洲或前苏联国家，美国和西欧曾经繁荣的社区变得空心化。随着全球经济消耗更多的自然资源，环境问题日益凸显。随着外国资金涌入和流出，一些经济体面临着不稳定的资本外逃。</p><p>经济学家表示，放松全球一体化——无论是出于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/friend-shoring-might-be-bad-for-global-growth-inflation-11654437600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国家安全、地缘政治竞争还是供应链焦虑</a>的原因——都会带来自身的问题。尤其面临风险的是较小的发展中经济体，如果它们想要通过贸易实现更大的繁荣，就需要进入全球市场。</p><p> “整个世界正在变得更加内向，并远离开放的贸易和投资，”前美国财政部官员、资产管理公司 TCW Group 新兴市场董事总经理戴维·洛文格 (David Loevinger) 表示。 “欧洲、美国和中国正在进行补贴竞争，而这场竞争的失败者是财政资源较少的较贫穷经济体。”</p><p>对于那些希望利用绿色技术来推动本国经济发展的国家来说，西方对产业政策的拥抱可能尤其痛苦。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834220?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Harita 在印度尼西亚经营的镍加工厂的一名工人。印度尼西亚希望利用其镍资源打造世界领先的电池产业。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ulet Ifansasti</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>印度尼西亚雄心勃勃，希望利用其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">丰富的镍资源</a>打造世界领先的电池产业。但作为爱尔兰共和军的一部分制定的美国规定，拒绝向含有大量来自非美国自由贸易伙伴国家的矿物的电动汽车电池提供补贴。印度尼西亚就是其中之一。</p><p> “我们拥有所有的自然资源。我们有人力资源。我们是一个民主国家，”说</p>印度尼西亚工商会会长阿尔斯贾德·拉吉德（Arsjad Rasjid）接受采访。 “请不要关闭我们。”<p></p><h3>获奖者</h3><p>作为补贴竞赛的领先者，美国正在经历投资热潮。根据联合国的数据，美国去年吸收了全球约 22% 的外国直接投资，成为全球最大的接受国。这略低于 2021 年全球投资在疫情期间暂停后反弹时的 26%，但明显高于 2019 年的 13%。5 月份与制造业相关的建筑支出与 2019 年相比增长了 76%。人口普查局数据显示，去年同期经季节调整后的年增长率为 1,940 亿美元。</p><p>在英国，纳科星公司的资金凸显了美国财力扭曲竞争环境的力量。除了去年筹集的私人资本外，Nexeon 还从英国政府电动汽车行业基金处获得了 200 万英镑，价值约 255 万美元。</p><p>几周后，根据 2021 年基础设施法引入的电池行业资助计划，Sila Nanotechnologies 和 Group14 Technologies 这两家美国竞争对手都从能源部获得了 1 亿美元的资金。与 Nexeon 一样，这些公司正在生产用于电池阳极的硅基材料，以提高性能。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="458" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834213?width=700&amp;height=458" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">北卡罗来纳州达勒姆市的一家半导体制造商 Wolfspeed 的工人们正在观看美国总统乔·拜登 (JoeBiden) 的讲话，这是他三月份美国投资之旅的一部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：梅丽莎·苏·格里茨/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>澳大利亚央行前副行长、西澳大利亚矿业公司 Fortescue <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/FMG" class="">Metals</a>旗下绿色能源部门 Fortescue Future Industries 现任董事盖伊·德贝尔 (Guy Debelle) 表示，“美国项目的经济性简直令人难以想象<span class="company-name-type">。</span> ” Debelle 表示，该公司正在寻找投资机会，目前认为美国是最有可能的投资地点，因为美国的补贴可能会使项目的价格降低高达 60%。</p><p>欧盟正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-to-compete-with-u-s-clean-tech-tax-breaks-by-loosening-subsidy-rules-87a7d334?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">准备自己的一揽子支持计划</a>，放宽成员国给予工业的补贴限制。到 2030 年，欧盟希望绿色转型所需的 40% 关键技术在欧盟生产，包括太阳能设备（目前由中国主导的行业）、风力涡轮机和电池。</p><p>据 Benchmark Minerals Intelligence 估计，自 IRA 宣布以来，衡量在建项目产能的美国电池生产线已增长 67%，目前与欧洲的规模相当，欧洲同期增长了 26%。收集行业数据的英国公司。</p><h3>英国脱欧问题</h3><p>对于英国来说，全球贸易的转变发生在一个特别尴尬的时刻，英国在 2020 年离开欧盟后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-prime-minister-rishi-sunak-tries-free-market-recipe-to-fix-britains-woes-2aa177b8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一直在努力</a>制定全球经济的新路线，这意味着它不再能够轻松进入其庞大的单一市场。</p><p>英国脱欧支持者表示，英国可以与其他国家达成双边贸易协议，并加大全球化力度。此后，自由贸易的势头陷入停滞，现在似乎正在倒退。</p><p>哥伦比亚商学院气候经济学家格诺特·瓦格纳表示：“在英国脱欧公投期间，没有人知道我们会看到美国产业政策的复苏。”</p><p>现在，英国政府面临着来自国内经济各个角落的呼吁，要求通过重振产业战略来应对全球经济的干预主义转向。</p><p>英国汽车业近期因捷豹路虎母公司选择<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-cinches-5-billion-ev-battery-plant-as-race-for-green-investments-heats-up-e20b142f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在英国新建电动电池工厂而</a>得到提振，但绿色补贴总体规模仍远远落后于美国</p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834215?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英国财政部长杰里米·亨特面临着引入重振工业战略以应对全球经济干预主义转向的压力。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Tayfun Salci/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>财政部长杰里米·亨特承诺在今年秋天公布英国的应对措施，但淡化了预期，并表示英国不会“在一些扭曲性的全球补贴竞赛中与我们的朋友和盟友针锋相对”。他表示，英国将寻求将资金投向英国具有明显竞争优势的领域。</p><h3>新联盟</h3><p>前世界银行贸易专家查德·鲍恩表示，对于无法竞争的国家来说，一个解决方案是拉近富裕贸易伙伴的距离，并从其产业政策中受益，就像加拿大和墨西哥通过与美国的自由贸易协定所做的那样华盛顿特区智库彼得森国际经济研究所的官员表示，印度尼西亚政府正在参与美国主导的印度-太平洋经济繁荣框架，该经济协定希望能够改善其矿产的市场准入。</p><p>去年，投资部长巴利勒·拉哈达利亚 (Bahlil Lahadalia) 表示，印度尼西亚将寻求组建一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mineral-rich-developing-nations-demand-bigger-piece-of-the-ev-pie-d1421603?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">类似欧佩克 (OPEC) 的镍镍卡特尔组织</a>，以回应电动汽车制造国的保护主义。镍是一种电池矿物，印度尼西亚的产量占主导地位。欧佩克模式的组织将与其他主要出口国协调镍生产水平，以确保价格上涨。</p><p>分析师对该计划表示怀疑，部分原因是其他镍生产商不想疏远美国和中国等强大的贸易伙伴。拉丁美洲的左翼领导人也提出了类似欧佩克的锂生产商组织的想法，但尚未付诸实施。</p><p>印度尼西亚和津巴布韦对镍、铝土矿和锂等矿产实施了出口限制，并要求外国公司在该国建立加工设施，作为出口的条件。</p><p> “我不喜欢这些政策，但它们显然很受欢迎，”瑞士圣加仑大学国际贸易和经济发展教授西蒙·埃文内特(Simon Evenett)说。 “显然，这会推高价格，并增加不确定性和风险。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834218?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Harita 在印度尼西亚经营的镍加工综合体的景观。印度尼西亚和津巴布韦对镍和其他矿物实施了出口限制。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ulet Ifansasti</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —伦敦的大卫·卢诺 (David Luhnow) 和悉尼的斯图尔特·康迪 (Stuart Condie) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给Ed Ballard（ <a href="mailto:ed.ballard@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ed.ballard@wsj.com）</a> 、Jason Douglas（ <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com）</a>和Jon Emont（ <a href="mailto:jonathan.emont@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jonathan.emont@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53<author><![CDATA[Ed BallardJason DouglasJon Emont]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>领导者</category><category>机械</category><category>电池</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>可再生能源设备</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>可持续发展/可持续发展</category><category>贸易壁垒/限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>政府援助</category><category>补助金</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>政治</category><category>可持续发展</category><category>可持续性</category><category>贸易壁垒</category><category>限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>机械</category><category>电池</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>可再生能源设备</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[You Made a Nice Profit Selling Your House? Beware What Happens Next]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一项研究表明，您很可能会为下一次支付多付钱<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001048402"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830957?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">根据最近的研究，卖家每获得一美元的净值收益，他们在下一次购房时就会多付 7.9 美分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Tiffany Hagler-Geard/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001048402"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/demetria-gallegos" itemprop="url" rel="author">德梅特里亚·加列戈斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 13 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-sell-profit-overpay-37d67253"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>随着房屋价值的上升，业主往往会对自己不断增长的资产感到满意。但根据最近的研究，房屋净值也有一个缺点：房主出售时拥有的净值越多，他们在购买下一套房屋时就越容易多付钱。</p><p>一项关于<a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4280776" target="_blank" class="icon none">住房财富和多付的</a>研究发现，购买价值 40 万美元的房屋时，拥有出售旧房净值的买家往往会平均多付约 8,000 美元，即 2%。该研究的合著者、加州大学洛杉矶分校安德森管理学院的经济学家 Gregor Schubert 表示，卖家每获得 1 美元的净值收益，他或她在下一次购房时就会多付 7.9 美分。因此，较高的股本销售往往意味着新房的多付款额更高。</p><p>该研究确定了两种主要理论来解释这一现象。第一，股本越高，资本限制就越少。因此，这些买家可以考虑购买更多的房屋，从而有可能找到更匹配且愿意支付更多费用的房屋。此外，受股票驱动的买家能够提供更多（有时确实如此），以避免费力地搜索有关新房价值的具体信息，或吓跑其他买家。在这两种情况下，这都可能导致报价高于实际需要。</p><p>为了得出结论，研究人员研究了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/Z" class="company-name">Zillow</a>从 1996 年到 2021 年 25 年的数据。平均家庭在出售房产前居住了 6.6 年，并实现了平均 86,244 美元的净资产收益，这相当于多付了 6,899 美元的房产税。下一个家。为了确定买家何时多付了钱以及多付了多少，研究人员分析了新房附近的房价趋势以及房屋的任何独特属性。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1000" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/7f17ba0e-f66a-49a0-86aa-343e58b01f9a-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>研究人员发现，当买家难以确定<em>特定</em>房屋的价格时，多付的可能性就更大。例如，当一栋房屋与附近的其他房屋不同时，或者容易观察到的数据点（例如年龄或卧室数量）不太能确定房屋的整体价值。研究人员表示，他们能够确定在这种情况下是否存在多付款项，部分是通过监控未来的销售情况，看看虚高的购买价格是否会导致持久的更高价值。</p><p>舒伯特说，为个人住房支付过高的费用会对整个社区产生影响，并导致全国范围内的住房成本不断上升。研究显示，卖家在房屋销售中每获得一美元的净值收益，附近社区的平均房价就会在未来六个月内上涨 8.9 美分。他表示：“当更多在其他市场获得大量销售收入的买家开始在某个特定城市寻找住房时，这往往会加速目标地区的房价增长。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为拥有大量房屋净值是否会让您更有可能多付购房费用？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>舒伯特建议不想多付钱的买家要注意，有钱但在比较购房过程中缺乏耐心，可能意味着他们会为下一套房子支付过高的费用。在价格快速上涨的热门市场中，买家应该考虑等到高收益买家不太可能不耐烦地抬高价格。</p><p>舒伯特说：“如果你想尽快成交，并且你在旧房子上赚了足够的钱，可以负担得起，那么更高的出价也许可以实现这一结果，但代价是你不太可能成交。”把房子转卖，获得高额利润。”</p><p>对于不需要抵押贷款的买家来说，与希望快速顺利地完成销售的房屋卖家协商折扣是很常见的。引用的一项研究发现， <a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3751917" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">全现金交易比抵押贷款交易有 11% 的折扣</a>。但舒伯特和他的合著者发现，拥有股权的全现金买家正在失去他们的优势。他说，“他们获得现金净折扣，然后折扣会因高股本超额支付而减少”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3B6959A8-71A5-4943-94C6-DE52E3AB8DD0&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhouse-sell-profit-overpay-37d67253&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">从纽约到奥斯汀，美国最大的城市都遍布着闲置土地。 《华尔街日报》解释了财产税在该国住房短缺中所扮演的不为人知的角色。照片插图：Amber Bragdon（3月出版）<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p><strong>德梅特里亚·加列戈斯 (Demetria Gallegos)</strong>是纽约《华尔街日报》的编辑。给她发电子邮件： <a href="mailto:Demetria.Gallegos@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Demetria.Gallegos@wsj.com</a> 。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/15cf4a50-10ac-4759-bf0a-9ac3cacda180.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-sell-profit-overpay-37d67253</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-sell-profit-overpay-37d67253<author><![CDATA[Demetria Gallegos]]></author><category>期刊报告</category><category>财富管理</category><category>财富</category><category>个人财务</category><category>财富报告</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>房地产</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>房地产清单</category><category>购买/出售房屋</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>期刊报告</category><category>财富管理</category><category>财富</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>房屋买卖</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>房地产清单</category><category>购买</category><category>卖房子</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>房屋买卖</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Can San Francisco Save Itself From the Doom Loop?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该市正在竞相为其市中心提出解决方案，该市中心因科技外流而空心化，并与无家可归和街头犯罪作斗争<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833049?width=1000&amp;height=562" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社；米凯拉·瓦切娃 (MICHAELA VATCHEVA) 为《华尔街日报》撰稿<span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128350"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128350"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jim-carlton" itemprop="url" rel="author">吉姆·卡尔顿</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/katherine-bindley" itemprop="url" rel="author">凯瑟琳·宾德利</a></span>Michaela Vatcheva 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 13 日上午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-crime-downtown-doom-loop-e5fcd7ba"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>当地领导人正在尽一切努力来维持旧金山陷入困境的市中心核心的运转，包括向退休的、手无寸铁的警察支付费用，让他们警惕麻烦。</p><p>其中一位是迈克·布朗 (Mike Browne)，他在旧金山当了 30 年警察，现在作为“社区大使”中队的一员在市中心巡逻，这些“社区大使”身穿蓝色衬衫，旨在帮助通勤者和购物者在旧金山<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-luxury-shopping-oasis-emerging-in-san-franciscos-struggling-downtown-35ad89e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">市中心商业区</a>及周边地区感到更安全<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-luxury-shopping-oasis-emerging-in-san-franciscos-struggling-downtown-35ad89e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">和购物区</a>。无家可归、吸毒以及商店行窃和汽车盗窃等非暴力犯罪在该社区的许多地方都很常见。</p><p>最近，当一名明显精神错乱的男子撞到他时，布朗什么也没做。 “你会怎样做？”这位60岁的老人说道。 “你不能疯狂战斗。”</p><p>旧金山市中心在 2010 年代的繁荣很大程度上得益于科技行业的发展。但这些员工在疫情期间很容易过渡到远程工作，而且大多数人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-commercial-real-estate-office-buildings-471742ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">从未全职回到办公室</a>。去年，迫于削减成本的压力， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CRM" class="company-name">Salesforce</a>等科技巨头解雇了员工，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-lyft-salesforce-and-other-tech-firms-dump-office-space-as-they-downsize-11668477701?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">削减了在该市的房地产业务</a>。市中心许多办公楼的楼层现在空无一人。</p><p>这些变化与旧金山多年来不断恶化的一系列相互交织的问题相冲突，包括高昂的住房成本、街头无家可归、猖獗的财产犯罪、芬太尼危机以及大流行以来公共交通乘客量的急剧下降。</p><p> “我感觉不安全，到处都是流浪汉，到处都是垃圾，”63 岁的桑德拉·布里利 (Sandra Brealey) 说，她是一名长期居住在这座城市的居民，以前经常去市中心，但在过去五年里基本上不再去市中心了。年。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833040?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">旧金山警察局退休警官迈克尔·布朗（左）和迈克·莫兰（右）在担任安全大使期间离开梅西百货。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="810" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834445?width=1260&amp;height=810" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2023 年 5 月 11 日，无家可归者在美国音乐学院剧院门口睡觉。市中心及附近地区无家可归和吸毒现象仍然普遍存在。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>旧金山市中心现在的经济健康状况几乎落后于其他所有主要城市中心。根据商业房地产公司高力<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CIGI" class="">国际 (Colliers International)</a>的数据，其写字楼空置率为 25.7%，比美国 16.4% 的空置率高出近 10 个百分点<span class="company-name-type">。</span>乘坐湾区快速交通列车前往市中心的乘客量是 2019 年水平的三分之一。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JWN" class="company-name">Nordstrom</a>和 Banana Republic 等零售商在过去几个月宣布将关闭旧金山市中心的商店。位于市中心的该市最大购物中心的所有者正在将其返还给贷方，而不是继续偿还债务。</p><p>旧金山的其他地区正在从大流行病的低迷中更快地恢复，餐馆和商店都人满为患。但市中心长期以来一直是这座拥有 808,000 人口的城市的经济引擎，创造了当地四分之三的国内生产总值。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="850" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834721?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>市政府官员表示，社区大使并不是解决市中心困境的解决方案，而是旨在防止该地区进一步恶化并进入经济学家所说的“末日循环”的几种创可贴之一。</p><p>城市末日循环始于与核心产业相关的触发事件，例如 20 世纪 70 年代制造业工作开始离开底特律。税收减少，服务受到影响，企业倒闭，混乱开始蔓延。居民离开，通勤者和购物者远离，这个循环自我强化。</p><p>对于旧金山市中心出现厄运循环的可能性有多大以及何时开始，经济学家们有不同的看法，但大多数人都认为需要做出重大改变来恢复社区的健康。</p><p> “旧金山是我最担心的城市之一，”纽约大学斯特恩商学院副教授阿皮特·古普塔（Arpit Gupta）说，他研究了城市末日循环。 “触发效应就在那里。”</p><h3>独特的脆弱性</h3><p>经济学家表示，旧金山比大多数其他城市更容易受到这一流行病的影响。近几十年来，它不断增加就业岗位，却没有与之相匹配的住房，它的劳动力只剩下两个相对没有吸引力的选择：在住房上花费大量资金，或者搬到更远的地方并忍受长时间的通勤。</p><p>随着大流行的发生，情况发生了变化。许多工人发现他们不需要支付旧金山的生活费，也不需要忍受旧金山的问题就能完成工作。 2020年至2022年间，该市人口下降7.5%，是美国人口超过5万的城市中下降幅度最大的。</p><p>据 CBRE 称，旧金山的科技公司目前占市中心可用转租空间的 76%。根据数据公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSGP" class="">CoStar</a>的数据，在疫情期间，Salesforce 将市中心的房地产足迹减少了 60% 以上<span class="company-name-type">。</span> Meta 的空间减少了 36%。</p><h4>金融区</h4><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/fader/0b35014c-6a2c-4990-8d27-e7f12c3b6f64.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>没有所有这些工人回来已经在市中心产生了连锁反应。</p><p> Jack&#39;s Shoe Repair Service 位于地铁出口前，那里曾经是大批通勤者经过的地方，店主 Setrak Soghomonian 表示，该店的业务量仅恢复了疫情前的 40% 左右。 Jack&#39;s 过去雇用了三名全职员工，但现在只剩下一名。</p><p> “只有当游客到来时，情况才会好转，”索格莫尼安说。 “普通人已经不在了。”</p><p>尽管旧金山正在全市范围内增加就业机会，但市中心的经济放缓影响了其税收收入。市主计长办公室预计，本财年收入将增长 0.6%，下一财年将增长 3.3%。 2018-19 财年，收入增长近 20%。上一财年增长了 7.9%。</p><p>无家可归和吸毒现象在市中心及其附近仍然普遍存在。事实证明，让无家可归者离开街道是很困难的，因为经济适用房长期短缺，而且联邦法院的命令使得很难违背他们的意愿将他们驱逐出去。</p><p>警察和大使部署最密集的地区是市中心的联合广场购物区。商家和购物者表示，入店行窃和骚扰行为因此减少。</p><p>但上班族仍然抱怨街头和地铁站的手机盗窃等犯罪行为。在毗邻市中心购物区的田德隆区，有开放的毒品市场。</p><p>尽管与其他主要城市相比，旧金山的凶杀率相对较低，但其财产犯罪率却名列前茅。在包括市中心在内的中央警区，与去年同期相比，2021 年汽车入室盗窃案件增加了 171%，去年增加了 2%，2023 年上半年增加了 3%。截至今年 6 月，入室盗窃案增加了 14%。</p><p> “合同是，你提供一个安全的做生意的地方，我提供税收，”前科技工作者、现在在一家名为 GrowSF 的非营利组织工作的史蒂文·巴斯 (Steven Buss) 说。 “在我们能够提供一个安全的做生意场所之前，我不知道企业是否会回来。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834444?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">金融区的 Wayfare Tavern。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833042?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">市场街上一家关门的商店。</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>人工智能的希望</h3><p>一些人认为人工智能公司将通过推动该地区的下一次科技繁荣来帮助旧金山市中心避免末日循环。</p><p>几家最有价值的人工智能公司，例如 ChatGPT 的开发商 OpenAI，都总部位于这里。 OpenAI 最近搬进了 Mission 区 60,000 平方英尺的办公空间，另一家人工智能公司 Hive 正在转租市中心一座建筑的三层楼。</p><p> “在世界其他任何地方，你都无法真正达到建立人工智能初创公司所需的速度和规模，”专注于人工智能领域的 Bloomberg Beta 投资者 Amber Yang 表示。</p><p>据世邦魏理仕称，今年第二季度旧金山租用或续租的 450 万平方英尺办公空间租户中，人工智能公司占近 18%。</p><p>但据高力国际称，人工智能行业还需要数年时间才能拥有足够大的公司，从而对旧金山的办公市场产生重大影响，旧金山的办公楼市场估计有 2500 万平方英尺的空置空间。</p><p>活跃于城市政治的企业家比拉尔·马哈茂德 (Bilal Mahmood) 表示：“即使拥有 500 家初创公司，也不等于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ABNB" class="">Airbnb</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DBX" class="">Dropbox</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span> Facebook、Google 拥有了数千名员工。”</p><p>他正在组织努力将一所大学校园迁至市中心，部分原因是他不希望旧金山在收入方面过于依赖某一行业，就像以前对互联网公司所做的那样。</p><p>城市领导人的另一个想法是通过用居民取代商业来使旧金山市中心更加活跃。该市已通过立法，使办公室改建为住宅变得更加容易。</p><h4><strong>内河码头</strong></h4><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/fader/851ad8c4-0387-49e3-9768-b650addde5a8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>旧金山规划总监 Rich Hillis 表示，市中心大约 500 万平方英尺的办公地产（不到目前空置面积的五分之一）可以改建为普通公寓或公寓。</p><p> Singular Builders 首席执行官杰夫·盖拉迪尼 (Jeff Gherardini) 表示，在首批项目之一中，Singular Builders 希望在今年秋天开始工作，将一栋建于 1908 年的历史建筑顶上的五层办公室改建为 40 间公寓。</p><p>但盖拉迪尼理解为什么潜在居民可能会持谨慎态度。他最近走进旧金山郊区的一家咖啡店，看到一名男子在背包里塞满了偷来的商品。 “我对此感到厌倦，”他说。</p><h3> “空虚到充满活力”</h3><p>由于大流行病和乔治·弗洛伊德被杀后的抗议活动以来退休人数增加和招募困难，旧金山是众多警察短缺的城市之一，但其 27% 的短缺尤其严重。</p><p>伦敦市长伦敦·布里德 (London Breed) 将警察加班预算增加了 2500 万美元，试图弥补原定 2,182 名警员中 599 名警员的缺口。</p><p>布里德在接受采访时表示，市中心正在改善，街道变得更加干净，她希望尽快让更多的人在那里工作和购物。一项名为“空置到充满活力”的计划旨在用具有相似主题（例如食品准备或艺术）的企业来填补空置的店面。</p><p>这位民主党市长表示：“我们必须把重点放在第一位，公共安全，第二位……以推动商业回到旧金山。”</p><p>她说，与此同时，社区大使正在帮助弥补差额。 “我想做一些事情，让具有执法专业知识的人成为街上的眼睛和耳朵，”布里德说。</p><p>该计划于 2020 年与包括 Browne 在内的 8 名前警察一起启动。现在全市有 74 名警官配备了警用无线电。</p><p>两年前，布朗和他的搭档迈克·莫兰在联合广场发现四名青少年在袭击一对老年夫妇并抢走他们的财物后沿着街道奔跑。他们用无线电报告了这一犯罪事件，几分钟之内，四人中的三人就被穿制服的警察逮捕了。</p><p> “否则他们不可能这么快到达那里，”65 岁的退休警察队长莫兰说。</p><p>旧金山计划在今年年底前再聘用 25 名大使，同时还寻求招募更多官员。</p><p> “这是整体解决方案吗？我不这么认为，”中士说。威尔·埃利夫（Will Elieff）负责监督中队。 “该部门正在将此视为解决方案的一部分。”</p><h3> 《我心科幻》</h3><p>今年旧金山经济最有希望的迹象之一是旅游业。官员们预计，今年将有 2390 万人次到访，高于 2022 年的 2190 万人次。尽管这一数字仍低于 2019 年 2500 万人次游客峰值，但酒店入住率已从疫情期间的 8% 低点反弹至 60%。旧金山酒店理事会。疫情爆发前，酒店已入住 80%。</p><p> John&#39;s Grill 是一家拥有 115 年历史的市中心餐厅，店主 John Konstin 表示，从 2019 年开始，今年的收入有望增长 20%。他将其归功于旅游业和更多的企业支出。 “公司又开始娱乐了，”康斯汀先生说。</p><p>房地产经纪人表示，也有迹象表明对办公空间的需求有所增加，过去一个季度寻求租赁的潜在租户数量激增。办公室工作人员表示，过去几个月里，他们大楼周围的街道看起来更干净了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833041?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">游客在旧金山联合广场拍照。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833043?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">缆车停在鲍威尔街。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>许多城市领导人指出，旧金山成功地从其他经济衰退中恢复过来，例如 2000 年互联网泡沫破灭和 1906 年地震。</p><p>但在更多人开始在市中心工作和购物之前，该地区仍面临进入末日循环的风险。</p><p>市政府办公室在 7 月份月度报告中发现，尽管该市其他大多数地方都出现强劲增长，但市中心写字楼市场几乎没有复苏的迹象。报告称，市中心的租金、办公室出勤率和交通乘客量基本持平。</p><p>一群当地慈善家正在尝试一种新策略：广告。</p><p>他们正在发起一项新的公民自豪感运动，以“我爱纽约”为蓝本，但旨在保留现有企业，吸引新企业，并改变对该城市的负面叙述。它将包括旧金山周围、商店和公交车站的广告和实物展示。</p><p>参与该项目的商业房地产开发商丹·金斯利 (Dan Kingsley) 表示：“旧金山过去在经济和文化方面对其在世界上的地位有点傲慢。” “没有太多的自我推销，这一点需要改变。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Peter Grant 和 Zusha Elinson 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给吉姆·卡尔顿（Jim Carlton）（ <a href="mailto:Jim.Carlton@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jim.Carlton@wsj.com）</a>和凯瑟琳·宾德利（Katherine Bindley）（ <a href="mailto:katie.bindley@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">katie.bindley@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 13 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-crime-downtown-doom-loop-e5fcd7ba</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/san-francisco-crime-downtown-doom-loop-e5fcd7ba<author><![CDATA[Jim CarltonKatherine Bindley]]></author><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>领导者</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>无家可归</category><category>住房问题</category><category>社会问题</category><category>入室盗窃/盗窃</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>无家可归</category><category>住房问题</category><category>社会问题</category><category>盗窃</category><category>盗窃</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Zelig’: Woody Allen as No One and Everyone]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位编剧兼导演的电影于 40 年前上映，将 1920 年代的档案片段与拍摄得像旧新闻片的新材料融合在一起，构建了一部反映我们这个时代的关于顺从的伪纪录片。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136172594871364"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832419?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">米娅·法罗和伍迪·艾伦在《Zelig》中</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Orion/华纳兄弟/Kobal/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136172594871364"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">彼得·汤盖特</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 5:37 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/zelig-woody-allen-as-no-one-and-everyone-3fbc16bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><strong>在伍迪·艾伦职业生涯的大部分时间里</strong>，他一直与某种浪漫喜剧联系在一起。在《安妮·霍尔》和《汉娜和她的姐妹们》等广受欢迎的电影中，艾伦先生用漫画描绘了 20 世纪末曼哈顿人的风流韵事。每个人都依赖于后来被视为公式的东西：口头戏谑、文化博学、视觉优雅，当然还有电影制片人自己在银幕上多嘴的忧心忡忡的形象。</p><p>然而这位 87 岁的编剧兼导演的职业生涯却充满了令人惊讶的弯路。他曾执导过德国表现主义传统（《影与雾》）​​、契诃夫（《九月》）和美国音乐喜剧（《人人都说我爱你》）；他最好的两部电影《赛末点》和《卡桑德拉之梦》都是谋杀故事。</p><p>毫无疑问，艾伦先生最大胆、最意想不到的成就是他 1983 年的电影《Zelig》。这部虚构的纪录片风格的电影旨在讲述爵士乐时代人物伦纳德·泽利格的神秘生活。泽利格由特别温顺、畏缩的艾伦先生饰演，他拥有一种深刻的从众本能，事实证明他既能将自己安排到意想不到的环境中，又能进行身体变形以适应各种场合。根据站在他身边的人的不同，泽利格会伪装成医生、黑帮和贵族。讽刺的是，这个角色的密码般的品质却赢得了广泛的声誉。</p><p>前提是超乎想象的；其中一个片段描绘了泽利格在两名肥胖男子附近，以一种心身顺从的行为，膨胀到很大的体重。尽管如此，艾伦先生认为这个故事是一个机会，可以严肃地讨论社会压力对个性造成的风险——“为了讨人喜欢，而不是制造麻烦，为了适应社会而放弃真实的自我，这是一种特殊的危险。”正如电影制片人在《伍迪·艾伦谈伍迪·艾伦》一书中向采访者斯蒂格·比约克曼解释的那样。</p><p>也许是为了强调他意图的严肃性，艾伦先生决定不在传统的戏剧场景中呈现所谓的人类变色龙的故事。相反，电影制片人采用了纪录片的形式，由一位庄严的叙述者（帕特里克·霍根配音）引导观众浏览城市景观、夜总会生活和跳舞的摩登女郎的档案镜头，所有这些都毫不费力地点燃了爵士乐时代的气氛。</p><p>然后，艾伦先生与电影摄影师戈登·威利斯一起拍摄了自己和其他演员的镜头——包括米娅·法罗饰演泽利格的精神病医生、红颜知己和最终的情人尤多拉·弗莱彻——以与旧镜头相同的颤抖和颗粒状方式。</p><p>电影剪辑师苏珊·E·莫尔斯 (Susan E. Morse) 优雅地将新旧材料拼接在一起，创造出真实和模拟的新闻片风格的镜头、照片和 20 年代音乐的网格。莫尔斯女士还明智地将艾伦先生放置在现有的镜头中，以便泽利格这个角色偶尔会与包括贝比·鲁斯在内的各种名人共享同一画面。</p><p>艾伦先生拍摄了对公共知识分子的采访，这些知识分子清醒地思考了泽利格的重要性，其中包括索尔·贝娄、欧文·豪和苏珊·桑塔格，这为影片增添了现实色彩。 “他是 20 年代的现象级人物，”桑塔格女士在令人窒息的评论中准确地说道。 “当你想到当时他和林德伯格一样出名时，真是令人惊讶。”任何曾经在公共电视上观看过此类节目的人都会认出艾伦先生对纪录片的惊人准确的模拟。</p><p>这一切加起来远远不仅仅是一项技术壮举（尽管威利斯因其摄影获得了奥斯卡提名）。通过精心的拼凑，这部电影对个人对现代社会的期望、正统观念和微妙的强制力量的反应进行了深刻的评论。尽管泽利格将这些压力内化到了极端、荒谬的程度，但我们每个人都可以认同他焦虑的根源：想要归属感、想要说正确的话、来自人群的帮助以及愿望沐浴在名人的光辉之中。就连影片的伪纪录片风格也反映了泽利格的真实本性。因为我们认为这个角色是一个遥远的人物，在据说是旧的剪辑和模糊的剧照中瞥见，所以他给人的印象与其说是一个全面发展的人，不如说是一个完整的人。<strong></strong>作为部落中的一个无足轻重的人——这正是他的本质。</p><p> “和其他人一样是安全的，”泽利格在与弗莱彻博士的一次催眠治疗中承认。他还揭示了他强迫模仿他人变得相当普通的根源：他认为，他的整个变形状况源于他曾经为自己是一群人中唯一没有读过《白鲸》的人而感到羞耻。当掩饰意味着显得更聪明、更有文化或更国际化时，我们中有多少人可能会忍不住掩饰？</p><p>上映四十年后，《Zelig》越来越不像是对过去时代的再现，而是对当下的寓言，人们比以往任何时候都更强烈地感受到随波逐流的压力。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。汤格特是《描绘彼得·博格丹诺维奇：我与新好莱坞导演的对话》一书的作者。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 21:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/zelig-woody-allen-as-no-one-and-everyone-3fbc16bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/zelig-woody-allen-as-no-one-and-everyone-3fbc16bc<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Eternal Truths Cast in Bronze: Rodin’s ‘The Gates of Hell’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>奥古斯特·罗丹未完成的项目是他作为现代雕塑之父和引人注目的人性肖像的遗产的基石。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827733" alt="奥古斯特·罗丹，《地狱之门》（演员 1926-28）" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>奥古斯特·罗丹，《地狱之门》（1926-28 年演员） 费城艺术博物馆<span>费城艺术博物馆</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126303181863836"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126303181863836"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">朱莉娅·费舍尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 5:45 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eternal-truths-cast-in-bronze-rodins-the-gates-of-hell-5ea6f0bb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>在奥古斯特·罗丹（Auguste Rodin，1840-1917）的整个职业生涯中，他眼中都是失败的。罗丹出生于一个贫穷的家庭，他曾三次申请进入巴黎美术学院——当时法国有抱负的艺术家的重要踏脚石——但一次又一次被拒绝。所以他必须自己走自己的路。他的雕塑经常遭到嘲笑和拒绝。直到三十多岁时，这位巴黎人的作品才引发了真正的兴趣——无论是积极的还是消极的。他的突破性雕塑《青铜时代》（1875）是一尊全尺寸的站立男性裸体，栩栩如生，以至于批评者指责罗丹直接从模型中制作模型。</p><p> 《地狱之门》被广泛认为是罗丹最伟大的作品，但也可能被认为是失败的。 1880 年，罗丹收到委托，为巴黎一座新的装饰艺术博物馆制作两扇带有浮雕的门，展示但丁的《神曲》。博物馆从未建成，但罗丹一直在创作《大门》，直到他去世——他生命的一半——此时它们仍未完成。最初的石膏模型现藏于奥赛博物馆，但 1917 年之后又制作了多个青铜铸件，可在世界各地的博物馆中看到。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"><a href="">奥古斯特·罗丹的《地狱之门》（1880-1917）</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap">青铜铸造的永恒真理</h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829113/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829113/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829113/">奥古斯特<span class="imageCredit">·罗丹费城艺术博物馆</span>“地狱之门”顶部的“三种阴影” </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829114/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829114/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829114/"> 《地狱之门》中的《思想者》，奥古斯特·罗丹费城<span class="imageCredit">艺术博物馆</span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829118/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829118/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829118/"> 《思想者》对《地狱之门》的另一种看法，奥古斯特·罗丹费城<span class="imageCredit">艺术博物馆</span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829115/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829115/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829115/"> 《坠落的人》是《地狱之门》的几位演员之一，奥古斯特·罗丹费城<span class="imageCredit">艺术博物馆</span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829117/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829117/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829117/"> 《地狱之门》中的《保罗和弗朗西斯卡》，奥古斯特·<span class="imageCredit">罗丹费城艺术博物馆</span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div><p>从远处看，门是一个宏伟的矩形形状，高 20 英尺，宽 13 英尺，复杂的形状像彩绘手稿边缘的藤蔓一样扭曲。近距离观察，它们几乎是可怕的。整个作品中充斥着人体的刺耳声音。虽然出现了大约 180 个人形，但在某一时刻出现的人数超过 200 人。罗丹以洛伦佐·吉贝尔蒂的《天堂之门》（1425-52）、佛罗伦萨洗礼堂的青铜门和米开朗基罗的《最后的审判》（1535-41）为模型。但在对受诅咒者扭曲身体的流畅、无等级的描绘中，罗丹创造了自己的东西。金属框架内的形态的动态运动永无止境。事实上，它们似乎并未受到遏制。灵魂向观众伸出援手，超越了门的界限。例如，在左上角，一个男性人物——“坠落的人”——像攀岩者一样倒挂着，他肌肉发达的手臂抓住了门楣。在他的下方，有一股混乱的旋风，他似乎决心要从中逃脱。</p><p>尽管罗丹最终放弃了对但丁诗歌的直接再现，但这座雕塑仍然显示了诗人的影响。罗丹最著名的作品“思想者”上方浮现出面孔和头骨。这个人物最初是为了代表但丁本人，后来失去了特殊性，而是象征着沉思。</p><p>在所有门内的人中，“思想者”的姿势可能是最静态的，但即使是这幅《大门》也展示了罗丹的天才。正如雕塑家所言：“我的思想者之所以思考，是因为他不仅用他的大脑、他皱起的眉头、他扩张的鼻孔和紧缩的嘴唇来思考，而且还用他手臂、背部和腿部的每一块肌肉，以及他紧握的拳头和嘴唇来思考。夹住脚趾。”这种身体特征在所有人物中都有体现。罗丹对人体解剖学的表现力处理几乎让人想起戈雅的画作。他不是简单地复制一种形式，而是捕捉身体背后发自内心的、完整的感觉力量。这既定义了“大门”，也解释了它们的重要性。自文艺复兴以来，艺术一直是一种讲故事的媒介。但在这里，罗丹抛弃了传统的叙事方式，让人类形成了自己的“故事”，仅用姿势和手势来表达思想和情感——在这种情况下，是人的悲剧命运。</p><p>因此，就像但丁的地狱一样，受诅咒的人彼此互动，既帮助又伤害。一男一女，但丁笔下的保罗和弗朗西斯卡，紧紧地抱在一起，不顾一切地想要保持彼此陪伴的舒适感。 （“吻”最初是门的一部分，也是受到悲剧恋人的启发。）在“思想者”的右边，惊慌失措的灵魂践踏和推挤。这位雕塑家在他那个时代受到严厉批评的原因是显而易见的：他的作品毫不畏惧地大胆、感性和风格化。对于尸体被抛在身后的永恒来说，罗丹的地狱是惊人的物质性。</p><p> The way that Rodin composed the “The Gates” broke with artistic convention as well. In places he recycles figures. The “Three Shades” at the top, for example, are casts of the same sculpture, anticipating Picasso&#39;s invention of assemblage—making sculpture out of pre-existing materials.</p><p> Rodin had a devout Catholic upbringing, and briefly joined a religious order after his beloved sister died. Beyond a fantastic depiction of a Dantean or even Christian netherworld, however, “The Gates” are a striking take on human suffering. Through his artistic rebellion, Rodin universalizes the tragedy he captures. The doors are populated not by demons armed with pitchforks, but humans whose unfulfilled longings cause them eternal agony. Created at the turn of the 19th and 20th centuries using sources from the Renaissance, “The Gates of Hell” nonetheless speak to us eloquently today. Admiring them on a fresh autumn day at Philadelphia&#39;s Rodin Museum, as I did nearly two years ago, one must still reckon with an internal hell.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。 Fischer is a Robert L. Bartley</p> Fellow at the Journal.<p></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 21:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eternal-truths-cast-in-bronze-rodins-the-gates-of-hell-5ea6f0bb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eternal-truths-cast-in-bronze-rodins-the-gates-of-hell-5ea6f0bb<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Dallas Museum of Art Picks a Winner]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The museum selects the Madrid firm of Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos for a makeover of its 1984 Edward Larrabee Barnes building. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126142695494342"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828306?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Aerial view of the winning design from Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos/Malcolm Reading Consultants </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126142695494342"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Michael J. Lewis</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 12:24 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-dallas-museum-of-art-picks-a-winner-9d3eedf0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Dallas</em></p><p> The Dallas Museum of Art announced today that it has selected the Spanish firm Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos, little known in the US, to remodel and expand its nearly 40-year-old building.</p><p> The DMA is a 1984 work of Edward Larrabee Barnes, an architect who made his mark with his dignified, politely modern museum buildings. It has aged rather well, and there was no question of demolishing it or remodeling it beyond recognition, as has been happening to the museums of his postmodernist contemporaries. Its problems are more logistic in nature.</p><p> Given a large rectangular lot in a forsaken edge district of car lots and parking garages, Barnes turned his building inward. He ran his main axis lengthwise through the site, making a kind of internal street some 650 feet long. To either side were the galleries, housed in square pavilions with plantings and paved walkways between them. He placed public entrances to the north, south and east, and surrounded the whole with a continuous border of trees. The idea seems to have been to get visitors inside the museum as quickly as possible, screened from what lies outside.</p><p> That was prudent then but no longer. Today the DMA is the centerpiece of a lively 60-acre art district, with two museums across North Harwood Street to the east and a large sculpture park to the north. Hence the search for an architect who could “strengthen its work with its communities, create stronger civic connections, transform the visitor experience with new facilities, and expand education and gallery space.”</p><p> Architects are normally chosen on the basis of their credentials and recent work, but the selection committee&#39;s consultant recommended that six architects be invited to make preliminary designs and each be paid a stipend of $50,000, plus expenses. At this, I was told by Jennifer Eagle, co-chair of the committee, “there was a gasp in the room.” But two donors stepped forward, leading to the most unusual architectural competition in recent memory.</p><p> Out of 154 applicants, the six firms were chosen, each with expertise in museum design or landscape and infrastructure. Normally architects compete in a void. In this instance they were flown to Dallas for three days so they could dine together and interact, then present their first impressions at a public forum on May 13, suggesting how they might approach the commission. By the morning of the presentation, they were high-spirited to the point of giddiness. Liz Diller, one of the competitors, joked that seeing former associates working for new firms was “like seeing former lovers with their new partners.”</p><p> On July 10, the finalists&#39; handsome models were unveiled and, to the relief of the selection committee, “there was not a Guggenheim among them!” But if there was no extravaganza of furious originality like Frank Gehry&#39;s Guggenheim Bilbao, the competitors varied widely in the degree of respect they accorded the work of Barnes.</p><p> At one end of the spectrum were the minimalists, such as David Chipperfield, who showed his “profound respect” for the original building by making his proposed interventions nearly invisible, except for a discreet new gallery constructed of timber. At the other end was Diller Scofidio + Renfro, which decided that Barnes&#39;s citadel should be “aloof no more.” Its proposal would have enclosed the museum at either end with mighty new entrance pavilions, the kind of wildly overscaled additions that dwarf the original into insignificance. One senses it would have swept away all of the original building if it could have.</p><p> The proposal of Michael Maltzan Architecture, of Los Angeles, was ostensibly more radical, but in a way that respected the essence of Barnes&#39;s original design with its internal street. Mr. Maltzan wanted to demolish everything along the museum&#39;s long North Harwood Street flank, opening up its internal street to a landscaped “cultural carpet” that would have run its length, forming a gently graduated transition from city to garden to museum. Above this carpet of green would loom a series of sleek glass pavilions, cantilevered into space and not touching the ground. In contrast to the earnestness of the other designs, this one offered a mischievous smile.</p><p> Weiss/Manfredi put the greatest stress on landscape, as might be expected from the designers of the visitors center at the Brooklyn Botanic Garden. Their inspiration came from Barnes&#39;s landscape architect, Dan Kiley, who gave the original building its character of an oasis in a desert. Johnston Marklee of Los Angeles, another firm that emphasized landscape, had one inspired architectural idea: to take the only curvilinear form in the Barnes building, the barrel-vaulted hall that forms the east entrance, and repeat it in new additions to the north and south. Unlike the Diller Scofidio + Renfro proposal, here were additions integral to the spirit of the original.</p><p> The committee was unusually sophisticated, with five professionally trained architects, including the director of the museum himself, Agustín Arteaga. In the end, it opted for what was easily the most subtle of the projects, that of Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos, whose approach was that of scrupulous microsurgery, not roughshod gesture making. Mr. Arteaga told me that they were struck by the firm&#39;s “respect for the Barnes legacy” even as it went about “opening up our fortress.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828307?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A view of Nieto Sobejano&#39;s expansive proposed gallery</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos/Malcolm Reading Consultants</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The most visible change Nieto Sobejano proposed was a large new gallery for the northwest end, anticipating future gifts. This was eminently in the Barnes mode, showing the same lean precision and rigor, if at a much larger scale. But what swung the decision in its favor, and about which Mr. Arteaga spoke with the most enthusiasm, was the way they changed the south entrance so you approach through a garden, “a simple and beautiful gesture” that puts you in the presence of art before you set foot in the museum; in all of this ran a spirit of “poetry,” a word that could not be easily applied to many of the other submissions. The museum made the correct choice.</p><p> Of course, this preliminary concept will be subjected to many changes in the years ahead. Will it succeed? Time will tell. But in one respect the Dallas Museum of Art has already triumphed, and that is in the novel and ingenious way it found its architect, something from which the world can learn much.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Lewis teaches architectural history at Williams and reviews architecture for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 04:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-dallas-museum-of-art-picks-a-winner-9d3eedf0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-dallas-museum-of-art-picks-a-winner-9d3eedf0<category>艺术评论</category><category>娱乐场所</category><category>博物馆/画廊/花园</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>建筑学</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> architecture</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>娱乐场所</category><category>博物馆</category><category>画廊</category><category>花园</category><category>闲暇</category><category>款待</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Goldfinch’: Carel Fabritius’s Rare Bird]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> This charming 1654 painting was made famous by Donna Tartt&#39;s 2013 novel, but its own story of survival and the mysteries that surround the work and its maker speak volumes on their own <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11216831118178654471904590070193167517222"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11216831118178654471904590070193167517222"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Willard Spiegelman</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 5:31 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-goldfinch-carel-fabritiuss-rare-bird-235a492f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822532?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;The Goldfinch&#39; by Carel Fabritius</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mauritshuis, The Hague</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Freud never said that sometimes a cigar is only a cigar, but whoever did so was right. Can an image with considerable iconic suggestiveness be only itself? Can a goldfinch be only a bird? The famous finch in Carel Fabritius&#39;s tiny oil painting perches on his little feeding box, overseeing a room in the Mauritshuis in The Hague. The picture shares pride of place with Vermeer&#39;s “The Girl With the Pearl Earring” as one of the most beloved works in this jewel box of a museum.</p><p> At 13.2 by 9 inches, “The Goldfinch” is not the smallest picture in the collection, but it is surely one of the most singular. Its subject alone separates it from the other dozen or so diminutive paintings—still lifes and portraits—at the Mauritshuis, as does its clear background instead of a heavily painted surface full of rich details. All the other small pictures seem crowded by comparison. This one, instead, feels ample and spacious as well as intimate. It opens itself up to us. This is a picture that breathes. The finch is a single figure on a white/gray background. Seen from across the floor, and behind a railing in front of his picture, he seems to come forward into the open room.</p><p> That the painting even exists today is a kind of miracle. It was in its maker&#39;s studio on Oct. 12, 1654, when the Delft gunpowder magazine exploded, killing at least 100 people, including the artist. He was 32 years old. Evidence suggests that the picture was still drying in the studio at the time of the disaster. Only about a dozen of the maker&#39;s other pictures survive.</p><p> Born in 1622, Fabritius came from a family of painters. He earned a place in Rembrandt&#39;s studio and moved to Amsterdam. Later, he relocated to Delft. His “Goldfinch” was largely unknown for two centuries. It began its modern life in 1859 when Théophile Thoré-Bürger, the man who revived Vermeer&#39;s reputation, discovered it in the collection of a Dutch army officer. Thoré-Bürger himself was given the picture in 1865. It arrived at the Mauritshuis in 1896.</p><p> Unlike Rembrandt and most of his pupils Fabritius favored light rather than dark settings. His interest in cool, harmonious colors served him well, especially with his finch. The white background, muted and mottled with gray and pink pastel shades, is a foil to the bird, who stands out from it.</p><p> The painting qualifies as a portrait-in-miniature. The finch is lighted from the left, his face less well-defined than his wings or his box, with its two bars and the almost imperceptible gold chain that attaches to him. Seen up close, the image hovers between precision and vagueness. Some authorities say that the bird&#39;s face has faded. It is quickly painted in thick strokes, à la Impressionism. The brown wing has a streak of yellow—the merest hint of “gold”—scratched in by the painter&#39;s brush handle. There are glowing highlights on the rings of the box feeder and on the bird&#39;s foot, backed by strong shadows on the wall. He seems alert, vigilant.</p><p> Even in so small a work, the geometry of the whole engages us. The bird&#39;s blue-gray, square feeder is centered. The finch looks to his right, and his body makes a diagonal line that cuts through the picture plane from upper right to lower left.</p><p> We know nothing about why Fabritius made this picture, or for whom. Perhaps it was part of a larger structure, like a window jamb. Or it may have been a piece in a larger assemblage of illusionary paintings. A 2003 restoration removed an old yellow varnish and brought back the original lighter background tones.</p><p> Whatever the artist&#39;s intent, his achievement continues to please and provoke. Does the picture possess meaning? For centuries, the goldfinch bore the weight of religious symbolism: It was associated with health, and with the Resurrection. It inspired devotional paintings. Raphael, Leonardo and Piero della Francesca,</p> among many others, inserted the bird into their work. The iconology retained its hold even after Fabritius&#39;s century, for example in Hogarth&#39;s 1742 painting “The Graham Children.”<p></p><p> The finch has had many lives. In our time, it inspired Donna Tartt&#39;s wildly successful 2013 novel “The Goldfinch,” and, among others, the poet Morri Creech and the painter Helen Frankenthaler.</p><p> Because we know so little about the maker and his motivation, quests for meaning remain moot, a grasping after what Keats, who preferred “mysteries, uncertainties and doubts,” dismissively called “fact and reason.” We must set significance aside, in favor of aesthetic enjoyment.</p><p> Still, this bird, restricted by his small gold chain, seems semi-liberated. In life, he would be capable of modest movement. You might also say that he frees us, his viewers, redeeming us from mental confinement.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Spiegelman&#39;s latest book, “Nothing Stays Put: The Life and Poetry of Amy Clampitt, ” has just been published by</p> Alfred A. Knopf.<p></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 21:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-goldfinch-carel-fabritiuss-rare-bird-235a492f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-goldfinch-carel-fabritiuss-rare-bird-235a492f<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Hispanic Society Museum & Library’s Quiet Restoration]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> After being closed since 2017, the institution has reopened after undergoing a series of subtle improvements and restorations in advance of its planned expansion <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10098652755748144108404589652850350819432"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791509?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Hispanic Society Museum &amp; Library</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nicholas Venezia/Selldorf Architects </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10098652755748144108404589652850350819432"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Michael J. Lewis</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> May 31, 2023 5:10 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-modest-upgrade-for-a-grand-building-73e07ad5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <strong>It is a remarkable</strong> testimony to the American capacity for national reconciliation that just six years after the bitter Spanish-American War a private citizen could create an institution that proclaimed to the world the glory of Spanish culture. The Hispanic Society was founded in 1904 by Archer M. Huntington, whose family&#39;s railroad fortune gave him free rein to indulge his love of Spanish art and literature. Believing that the public should have access to his private collection, he found a site at 155th Street and Broadway in New York&#39;s then fashionable Washington Heights. There he built the superb museum and library that is one of New York&#39;s triumphs of Renaissance Revival architecture.</p><p> The Hispanic Society is now looking forward to a renaissance of its own. It reopened in May having been closed since 2017. It will soon undertake a major expansion, planned by Selldorf Architects, working in collaboration with Beyer Blinder Belle and landscape architects Reed Hilderbrand. But it has now gotten off to an unexpectedly early start with what the architects jokingly call an “accidental restoration.”</p><p> The vast architectural ensemble on which the Hispanic Society sits is itself somewhat accidental. Huntington built his museum and library as a freestanding object on a terrace, a jewel box in a park. But no sooner had he completed his museum than he was coaxing other institutions, on several of whose boards he sat, to join him. He would give them building sites on condition that they build within five years and on plans approved by him. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791510?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Inside the Hispanic Society</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alfonso Lozano/The Hispanic Society</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The first two were built in 1909, the Numismatic Society to the west and the American Geographical Society across the terrace to the north. The Museum of the American Indian followed in 1916, adjoining the Hispanic Society to the east. The last to build was the American Academy of Arts and Letters, added to the far west of the terrace in 1921. It is perhaps the largest collection of learned societies ever to be shoehorned onto a city block.</p><p> All of these buildings, except for the American Academy, were designed by Charles P. Huntington, Archer&#39;s cousin. (He also designed Our Lady of Esperanza, built to give the complex a Catholic church in which Spanish was spoken.) They have an exquisite visual unity that comes from their construction in Indiana limestone, their continuous cornice height and the repetition of the colossal Ionic order. Arrayed on a monumental axis over 500 feet in length, they represent the urbanism of the City Beautiful at its best.</p><p> Or rather would have, if the axis actually led somewhere. By the time Huntington realized he was building a cultural acropolis, developers had taken the parcel at the west end of his site. Rather than pointing majestically to the Hudson and the Palisades beyond, his formal ensemble leads to the 11-story Riviera apartments, at whose unlovely brick buttocks its heroic axis dies.</p><p> Beginning in the 1980s, most of the cultural institutions pulled up stakes and moved elsewhere. But this presented the Society with an opportunity. It could now expand eastward into the former Museum of the American Indian (whose collections had been transferred to the Smithsonian). Here it will be able to display more of its permanent collection, the bulk of which is in storage, but also have room for temporary exhibitions. In preparation for that campaign, and to announce that the Society was about to awaken from its slumbers, it decided to improve access to its Sorolla Gallery, the room that Huntington added in 1914 to house the “Vision of Spain,” Joaquín Sorolla y Bastida&#39;s 14-painting cycle celebrating the geography and life of that country. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"> <a href="">&#39;Vision of Spain&#39; (1911-1919)</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap"> Selections from the monumental, 14-painting celebration of his native country by Joaquin Sorolla y Bastida, the preeminent Spanish artist at the turn of the 20th century. </h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791979/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791979/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791979/"> Left: &#39;Navarra&#39;, 1914; Right: &#39;Aragón&#39;, 1914 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791980/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791980/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791980/"> &#39;Cataluña&#39;, 1915 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791981/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791981/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791981/"> &#39;Ayamonte&#39;, 1919 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791982/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791982/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791982/"> Detail of &#39;Castilla&#39;, 1913 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791983/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791983/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791983/"> Detail of &#39;Castilla&#39;, 1913 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791984/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791984/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791984/"> Left: &#39;Valencia&#39;, 1916; Right: &#39;Sevilla, The Dance&#39;, 1914 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791985/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791985/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791985/"> Left: &#39;Sevilla, The Bullfighters&#39;, 1915; Right:Detail of &#39;Castilla&#39;, 1913 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791986/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791986/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791986/"> Installation view <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791987/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791987/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791987/"> Installation view <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791988/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791988/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791988/"> Installation view <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div><p> The latest project was modest, little more than adding emergency lighting, new signage, and ADA disability lifts for the multilevel terrace. But even so, the bids were shockingly under the roughly $10 million budget—something that almost never happens. The startled architects realized they could restore the original building and the covered courtyard at its center. After the formal dignity of the facade, this space comes as a happy surprise. A kind of Spanish cloister, it consists of an open central space surrounded by an arcaded walkway of deep-red terra cotta, Renaissance in style and richly ornamented.</p><p> But it had fallen into disrepair, and both the terra cotta and the floor of red Mercer tile were badly chipped and missing pieces. All were given a deep cleaning, the missing elements patched, a new system of flexible lighting installed, and the plaster walls rendered in neutral gray (the kindest background against which to hang paintings). The architects did not re-create the original skylight, alas. That was removed long ago when the building received a new copper roof. Instead, they plan to install electric lights above the laylight over the space, suggesting daylight. Otherwise, this is the best kind of restoration, the one that is practically invisible.</p><p> But the real challenge for the Hispanic Society was never technical but psychological. Over time it had come to seem like a private club rather than a public institution. With the first phase of the restoration it has now rolled out its red carpet. One hopes its heavily Dominican neighborhood—and New Yorkers in general—will accept the invitation to Huntington&#39;s quirky, plucky institution created to honor the Spanish and Portuguese-speaking cultures of the world.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Lewis teaches architectural history at Williams and reviews architecture for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 31 May 2023 21:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-modest-upgrade-for-a-grand-building-73e07ad5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-modest-upgrade-for-a-grand-building-73e07ad5<category>艺术评论</category><category>建筑学</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> architecture</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Gilder Center’s Architecture Is an Expression of the Earth]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In its fluid, free-form design, the American Museum of Natural History&#39;s new addition evokes the gentle contours that come from living processes acting over deep time. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10416900472008133444704589584271495422130"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-772117?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Richard Gilder Center for Science, Education, and Innovation</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Iwan Baan </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10416900472008133444704589584271495422130"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> Michael J. Lewis</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated April 29, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-gilder-centers-architecture-is-an-expression-of-the-earth-93323e2c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>New York</em></p><p> <strong>Is there a museum</strong> anywhere that has not just built an addition? If not, it soon will. Ours is a museum-enlarging age. An architect can build a lucrative practice on that fact (one thinks of Renzo Piano or Annabelle Selldorf ).</p><p> But additions are a tricky business. You tamper with a landmark at your peril, as Michael Graves learned with his radical proposal of the 1980s to absorb the Whitney Museum within a postmodern colossus. It&#39;s much safer to design a neutral box that offers no visual competition. Or to practice museological social distancing, as when Mr. Piano set his 2013 addition to the Kimbell Art Museum away from Louis Kahn&#39;s sublime building.</p><p> It is nonetheless possible to enlarge a museum in a way that is expressive of the present moment, that is poetically evocative of its purpose and content, and that does not stick out like a sore thumb. Such is the lesson of the Richard Gilder Center for Science, Education and Innovation, Studio Gang&#39;s $465 million addition to the American Museum of Natural History in New York, which opens May 4.</p><p> The AMNH is a patchwork of a building, a four-block sprawl along the west side of Central Park and more than a century in the making. It was envisioned as a foursquare citadel in red granite, with round towers at the corners and a burly Romanesque portal at the center of each side. Only the south wing was fully realized, and while monumental entrances were eventually built to the east and north, the west side languished.</p><p> In 2014 Studio Gang was commissioned to design a 230,000-square-foot addition that would provide exhibition and classroom space and also serve as a new entrance pavilion. But it had to do still more. Because the Romanesque master plan had never been completed, many of the passages were dead ends, which the addition was expected to open—with no fewer than 33 connections. A tall order, like expecting the missing piece of a jigsaw puzzle not only to fit but to transform the rest of the puzzle. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-772110?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The atrium at the Gilder Center</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Iwan Baan</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The new pavilion is an essay in free-form design, fluidly curved within and without, and is not so much biomorphic as geomorphic. Jeanne Gang, the founder of Studio Gang, told me that she was inspired by the image of “a canyon, worn down by wind, weather and water.” Instead of a literal facsimile of nature, she wanted to evoke it abstractly, through the gentle contours that come from living processes acting over deep time.</p><p> Free-form design can be a breach of architectural good manners, but Ms. Gang&#39;s canyon inspiration works better than expected. It is aligned with the museum&#39;s crucial east-west axis on West 79th Street, which is itself a canyon of tall buildings, and it opens itself to the street grid in a way no other part of the museum does.</p><p> Yet at every step it defers to the older buildings, and not only by matching their height. To either side of the cleft, the facade swells outward in a nod to the Romanesque towers; meanwhile the same pink granite is used as the entrance on Central Park West.</p><p> The interior, a five-story well of light and space, is a rhapsody of flowing structure. Its walls billow and swell, and then abruptly pucker into an opening; it suggests what it would feel like to be inside a Henry Moore sculpture. Its curved surfaces are composed of shotcrete, concrete hosed at high pressure onto a steel rebar cage, forming both the structure and the visible surface. The treatment of the surfaces has been carefully studied to give them a fine-grained handmade texture, one of those subtle tactile refinements that one senses but does not consciously notice. Another is the light, which pours in from the full-height curtain wall of the entrance and from three circular skylights, and which takes on a superb and gentle softness as it reflects off the irregular curves. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-772118?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Gilder Center&#39;s library</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alvaro Keding/AMNH</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> This ceremonial hall is not the only great space in the Gilder Center. The fourth-story reading room is a cozy tent of a space, its hefty central column carrying a great spread of structural ribs; one might as well be reading under a mighty oak tree, which feels continuous with the canopy outside the oversized window. Ms. Gang worked to make sure all her windows were treated to be visible to flying birds (she spoke movingly of her distress at “the small songbirds whose long journey of migration ends on a sheet of glass”).</p><p> Where necessary, the architecture recedes into invisibility, as in—appropriately enough—“Invisible Worlds,” an immersive and interactive experience that takes place in a 5,800-square-foot oval space. But this is a windowless exception in a building that is otherwise conspicuously, even extravagantly, lavish with sunlight.</p><p> It was not long ago that museums arranged their collections to depict a system of order, either an evolutionary sequence (as with natural history or art) or a structure of interrelationships (as with anthropology). To endorse any sort of systematic order has increasingly come to be seen as arrogantly elitist, and many exhibitions, in the US and elsewhere, have been reconfigured to express a multiplicity of interpretations. The consequence is a distressing sense of uncertainty.</p><p> But there is nothing uncertain about the Gilder Center. Its structure and space celebrate nature, in all its splendor and complexity, and not—miracle of miracles—the architect who designed it.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Lewis teaches architectural history at Williams and reviews architecture for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Apr 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-gilder-centers-architecture-is-an-expression-of-the-earth-93323e2c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-gilder-centers-architecture-is-an-expression-of-the-earth-93323e2c<category>艺术评论</category><category>Technical Services</category><category> Architects</category><category> Design Services</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>建筑学</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> architecture</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>technical services</category><category> architects</category><category> design services</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>房地产</category><category>建造</category></item></channel></rss>